    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it

    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know

    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Changed 'start' -> 'restart' to apply changes

Apache HTTP and memcached are already installed and after then they
are automatically started after each service installation from
the previous steps. To apply configuration changes, restarting
services is required. However, when users execute starting services,
the changed configuration will not be applied to the system.

Change-Id: I1b04a96ce5e92a1fd70dc8f40c346fda790266ce
Partial-Bug: #1467994

commit_message:
Changed the note because it restarts two services

The current note says that only Apache HTTP service is
restarted by systemd command. However, the command actually
restarts both Apache HTTP service and memcached service.
Therefore, the note should be changed that the command restarts
each service.

Change-Id: Idcfc67f8e64defc1c65c9252c85a0a371633a91c
Partial-Bug: #1467994

commit_message:
Changed the note because it restarts two services

The current note says that only Apache HTTP service is
restarted by systemd command. However, the command actually
restarts both Apache HTTP service and memcached service.
Therefore, the note should be changed that the command restarts
each service.

Change-Id: If792a6794822c33439555af716946ee426a02ef6
Partial-Bug: #1467994

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Because python creates pyc files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

Change-Id: I948892fb820f3d0583731627068ae3aa254121e7
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Fixed tox exec warnings with obsolete deletion

Current tox execution generated total three warnings.
Two warnings are from checkdeletions and checklinks,
both of which are obsolete now.
The other warning is from checklang because bash command
is in /bin, not in testenv:checklang environment.

So this patch removes some tox obsolete sections:
checkdeletions, checklinks and checksyntax as well,
and adds bash to whitelist_externals in checklang.

Change-Id: If514445272ef9fb5e0f182ba8407e195adaa0b62
Closes-Bug: #1518413

commit_message:
make pep8 faster

This builds a stripped down tox target for pep8 that doesn't need a
giant venv with all the things. Works fast and lean, and makes julien
fries.

Change-Id: Id5b7671fb7f2b8cbf88745fd12f9238b3c0bb2dd

As of version 3.0, MongoDB no longer reports "connected as:..." in
the output of mongostat. This causes the guest agent status checking
function to not work. This changes it to not grep for connected but
just check the return code from the mongostat call as it will return
non-zero if mongo isn't running or reachable.

Change-Id: If1329a5338ecaffd11919183eda640ee56635794
Closes-bug: 1448185
(cherry picked from commit 4d16c8384a4add5be637086a7df84205c75cc047)

commit_message:
Fix Mongo status check to work for Mongo 3.0

As of version 3.0, MongoDB no longer reports "connected as:..." in
the output of mongostat. This causes the guest agent status checking
function to not work. This changes it to not grep for connected but
just check the return code from the mongostat call as it will return
non-zero if mongo isn't running or reachable.

Change-Id: If1329a5338ecaffd11919183eda640ee56635794
Closes-bug: 1448185
(cherry picked from commit 4d16c8384a4add5be637086a7df84205c75cc047)

commit_message:
Fix issues in Glance filesystem backend

The glance images are stored in the api contaienr, not the registry
container. This is not a direct cherry-pick because the master branch
patch contained the drop-root changes along with this change
preventing a direct cherry-pick.

Change-Id: Iadc5ee4f94801a2194995c64f0cbd457220183cd

(apply same fix that we did for keystone, to horizon)

In some cases we're seeing httpd not cleaning up properly after itself,
which results in the horizon container failing to restart. This is
confirmed to happen on rpm based distros, but have not had any reports
on Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I8ece6da1a8a1180730d68be0d129a656ddcede07
Closes-Bug: #1515214
backport: liberty
(cherry picked from commit bac1235ed200bb7694e286cdc80f689f25f871ef)
"}]
commit_message:
Clean up horizon httpd pid files for RPM distros

(apply same fix that we did for keystone, to horizon)

In some cases we're seeing httpd not cleaning up properly after itself,
which results in the horizon container failing to restart. This is
confirmed to happen on rpm based distros, but have not had any reports
on Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I8ece6da1a8a1180730d68be0d129a656ddcede07
Closes-Bug: #1515214
backport: liberty
(cherry picked from commit bac1235ed200bb7694e286cdc80f689f25f871ef)

commit_message:
Fix namespace regression for neutron

Due the to way network namespaces work, they will not survive a
container restart. This is not an issue related to Kolla or Neutron
but rather an issue with how network namespaces work.

This is putting back into place a workaround that was in correctly
removed in the past. We simply cleanup the namespace cruft when the
neutron-agents container restarts thus avoiding this issue.

Change-Id: Ic16f2f766b4fa46347ea14a1ece5a4653c69d779
Closes-Bug: #1511216
(cherry picked from commit baf9d93358f8fc79df9bb71f24dbc50b85860ea1)

commit_message:
Move cors allowed_origin check into add_origin

This fixes an issue caused by c4957606cb290a639a4a02fbf648044242c5c207
where the add_origin method would fail if allowed_origin was
set to None. This could occur (even if oslo_config_project was
also set) if the projects config file contained its own
[cors] section anyway.

By moving the 'if allowed_origin:' check into add_origin
we ensure the function handles the default value if it
ever gets called.

Change-Id: I643e7a50e62564741fda784846bbdf3eb2bcc715
Closes-bug: #1518112

commit_message:
Switch to using neutron.common.utils:replace_file()

neutron.agent.linux.utils:replace_file() and
neutron.common.utils:replace_file() have same functionality.

This is the final patch in a series of 4 patches.
It marks neutron.agent.linux.utils:replace_file() for removal.

Closes-bug: #1504477
Depends-On: Id0eb6829ce75df5ffccc354adfe2f0ccb19ed9fd
Depends-On: I4352b7f1d6a55e47bbff4f3a1fcf136ed645dcbe

commit_message:
Add manual cleaning to state machine

This adds transitions to the state machine so that manual cleaning can
be performed on a node in the manageable provision state via the
'clean' verb. After cleaning is successfully finished, the node will
be in the manageable provision state again (via the 'manage' verb).

The state machine diagram was updated to reflect this.

Change-Id: Ifacdcceb65d1384351aa832042a7471bb48f0894
Implements: blueprint manual-cleaning

LGTM, thanks Lucas'}, {'account_id': 10342, 'date': '2015-11-16 21:56:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I'm thinking this needs to be optional.

Think about this scenario: 
- It takes me 30 seconds to download my image, because my network is blazing fast.
- It takes me 5 minutes to write the image to disk, because my disk is amazingly slow.

With this change, and no choice to disable it, I'm now going to hold a connection open to swift (or wherever my image is) for 5 minutes, whereas before it'd only be open for 30 seconds.

While I know this is an extreme edge case; it's a case I have and would be very concerned this would hurt performance for me in this case.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-11-17 11:17:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Jay,

Right, I haven't thought about this use case and I agree with it.

The configuration tho should be in Ironic when it calls prepare_image() it should signalize somehow the IPA ramdisk to just stream it directly to the disk (if the image is raw). I will cook a patch to Ironic and then update this one.

Thanks for the review"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-11-17 12:22:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-11-17 12:23:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add support for streaming raw images directly onto the disk

This patch adds support for streaming a raw image directly onto the disk,
that means no more time spent writing the image to a tmpfs partition prior
to copying it to the disk. Checksum computation is also done as the image
is being streamed. Streaming raw images is disabled by default, however
this behavior can be enabled by passing a key called "stream_raw_images"
with the value of True to the prepare_image() command of IPA.

For non-raw images this may not be possible, not sure about all image
file formats, but common types such as qcow2 requires random access to
the image file in order to be converted to raw.

Closes-Bug: #1505685
Change-Id: Iddf67907bc9b54bbd3065a97064cb5a3602cfe18

commit_message:
Change return value from 202 to 200

os-tenant-networks create returns 200 if it succeed.
so we need to change it from 202 to 200.

Change-Id: I0457251c1b81f42c7ff78d003a4369f7403ff508

@Tom or @Egor, could you help explain ?
Thanks'}, {'account_id': 12612, 'date': '2015-11-03 03:05:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(6 comments)

In addition to the comments, this should also have a cosponsoring patch to project-config to add the jobs to the gate as non-voting.

Once the non-voting jobs prove to work, and when it feels comfortable, the jobs can then change roles, switching -constraints to voting and the non-constrained version to non-voting.


Kai:  The goal of -constraints is to allow centralised control over project requirements to reduce gate breakage and stop arbitrary pinning in requirements.txt that has caused significant pain to stable releases.  More details can be found at http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/requirements-management.html'}, {'account_id': 12612, 'date': '2015-11-03 03:05:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 12175, 'date': '2015-11-04 01:41:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add -constraints sections for CI jobs

Tox does not currently support using factors with sections, and work
towards enabling this has stalled, as such we will need to duplicate
sections adding -constraints to facilitate running sections with the
constrained install_command.

Author: Tom Cammann <tom.cammann@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Egor Guz <guz_egor@yahoo.com>
Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management
Change-Id: Ia36b1794077f29eac189e19552c2d3a4bfe26e5e

Add Access Control bug tag

Provide tag for bugs that affect the role based access control
and the Neutron policy layers (driven by policy.json).

commit_message:
Make sure timeouts are floats

timeouts passed to iterate_timeout need to be int or float. If something
goes south and a timeout gets converted to a string, this blows up.
Luckily, python is good at converting string floats to real floats.

Change-Id: I3489532f0e43e1c289ecb50c77dd80e47ac65ab2

commit_message:
Allow specifying cloud name to ansible tests

It would be *really* cool and useful and stuff to be able to run
the Ansible playbooks against more than just devstack. This change
allows that. Now you can send the -c option to the tox command line:

    tox -e ansible -- -c coolcloud

Or, specific tests:

    tox -e ansible -- -c coolcloud auth network

Going against devstack is still:

    tox -e ansible
    tox -e ansible auth network

Change-Id: I666a09aee3d283865c3813d67edfb75123057c22

commit_message:
Do not send 'router:external' unless it is set

There are some setups where sending 'router:external' can
produce a Forbidden error. For an example, see:

  https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/issues/2435

Let's not send it unless it is explicitly set to True.

Change-Id: I59c43bf3eab09ed620cd1e8e5e445037767eb8bb

commit_message:
Remove default values from innner method

There are node codepaths where we want to not pass in values to
_upload_image_task - so remove the default values because they're
confusing.

Change-Id: I3575e9d7f31548aa99ef58bca15dfc8042155855

commit_message:
Revise help message of '--docker-volume-size' for baymodel-create

This patch revise help message of '--docker-volume-size' for
baymodel-create to be able to know how to set this parameter
to user (tell user this parameter is number in GB).

Change-Id: Ifb30451f8f5fcbe45e47fe6f78e506e9107b63b8
Closes-Bug: #1518143

commit_message:
Bugfix release of os-client-config

We found a tiny untested interface that got messed up in the last
release. This fixes it and also adds tests for the interface.

Needed-By: If1656214d17d32c5724bc5bb7faa6df85b311bb6

commit_message:
Fix a 60 second unit test

The no-addresses test was waiting for delete timeout and was therefore
sticking around for 60 seconds for a sideeffect we did not care about.

Add a second get return value so that the get in delete returns without
a wait-poll loop. Also, set the list server interval to 0 so that we
done have a bunch of tests with a single 6 second wait.

Change-Id: Ia62ace386a183892f9446aee4e9d4cbbee528dec

commit_message:
Switch to puppet-community/mcollective module

Our in-house module hasn't received much maintenance during last
releases, and the external one will allow us to use SSL for secure
mcollective communication.

The new module pulls richardc/datacat as a dependency.

Closes-Bug: 1508058
Depends-On: I26ac4110e1e2abd9ea2caa4954958a161dc5e204
Change-Id: I1657ce22be62414abd4a407a5d28292f25915a7b

commit_message:
autohelp: avoid help strings on multiple lines

Multiple lines means dealing with indentation, which is complicated and
not a problem for automatically generated tables. Use the same helptext
generation in autohelp than in extract_swift_flags.

Change-Id: Ibd64d3f0387c3e7f1f3aacf57be5f0c97addf5c9

commit_message:
Note that you should disable q-l3 with OVN_L3_MODE.

Add a note to devstack/local.conf.sample that you should disable q-l3 if
you enable OVN_L3_MODE.  Also make the devstack plugin fail if q-l3 is
enabled with OVN_L3_MODE set to True.

Change-Id: I60d9e9415e193924b5a258268eda84bc7e461dc2
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Adding dev-notes for try-catch block in periodic task

Not removing existing try-catch block for sync_bay_status and other
periodic tasks. Rather leaving a note with the pointers and explanation
for developers to add new periodic task.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-11-16 22:41:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Added VAG support to SolidFire

This patch adds VAG support to the SolidFire driver.
This includes a new config option 'sf_enable_vag'.
The driver creates a new VAG based on initiator name during
connection initialization.

By default VAG support is disabled. When enabled, the driver uses both
CHAP and VAG authentication.

DocImpact
Added configuration option sf_enable_vag.

Change-Id: I4ade805640646173c27bc6d969a211189f6301fb

their location. And link for yaql repository

they are opening with double muranopackages,hot packages
in their url's. so I removed one muranopackage and placed
 "./"

Closes-Bug: #1491197

commit_message:
Fix use of fields argument in get_rbac_policies

The 'fields' argument wasn't being passed into the _get_collection
call so the results were always coming back with all of the fields.
This adds an API test to prevent a regression.

Change-Id: Iddef9dcc7639a557a9d19dc7265f10f98e002172
Closes-Bug: #1517815

commit_message:
Remove misplaced copyright attribution

the module neutron.api.extension has a copyright attribute to a user
who never contributed a line to this module. It was probably copied
over in the initial commit for the module.

This commit is probably quite pointless; however it removes a little
oddity and does no harm to anyone.

Change-Id: I985bf2cb0538a795464dfe783108f218f821d762

was to keep consistency with rabbitmq and mariadb, but in light of

commit_message:
Move data container to start.yml

The original reason for having the data container in the bootstrap.yml
was to keep consistency with rabbitmq and mariadb, but in light of
this bug we need to move the data container out of the bootstrap.yml
role since we will be limiting the hosts that those tasks can run on.

Change-Id: I7f2f5979b01807275908699d1243756cb97d3588
Partial-Bug: #1513598
(cherry picked from commit 564f8f2bd484181ea46041932befbbe9bc67afb3)

In Ie2e57b76717604f701daa16ebf8ffa8c06835e3c, we switched
from StrOpt to ListOpt for allowed_origin configuration
option. For example ironic uses set_override to set
the value to a string in test cases. We should allow

Change-Id: Ifac325871d89d9e85c6e74c05ba6e004aeb741b9
'}]
commit_message:
Backward compat for allowed_origin

In Ie2e57b76717604f701daa16ebf8ffa8c06835e3c, we switched
from StrOpt to ListOpt for allowed_origin configuration
option. For example ironic uses set_override to set
the value to a string in test cases. We should allow
the older behavior for some time to allow ironic
test case TestCORSMiddleware to switch over.

Change-Id: Ifac325871d89d9e85c6e74c05ba6e004aeb741b9

commit_message:
Refactoring HP 3PAR Cinder Driver to be HPE

The HP 3PAR Cinder driver was recently refactored to be HPE.

The same refactoring is being done to the documentation with
this patch. It is being done because the company managing the
HP 3PAR Cinder driver is now Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE).

Closes-Bug: #1516076
Change-Id: Ie3857fdeb7aee371a3f081d93c423dcfff764cd2

full disclosure:

the change as-is bumps the complexity of save() from 23 to 25 (by inclusion of an inner function and the if statement), which doesn't change it's ranking as the second highest method in Instance, but inches it closer towards _from_db_object()'s 29.  Max complexity for Nova is set to 35.

there's no way around the if statement (we either exit from the inner function early or use a function variable which we override), but if we move the inner function out to the class, then we minimize the increase in complexity to 24 but have to resort to function variable overriding (which is not the most intuitive, imho).

i believe it is "simpler" as contained in this patchset, but in case somebody is concerned about increased cyclomatic complexity to an already complex method.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-11-18 21:43:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Prevent redundant instance.update notifications

Use _sync_cells within Instance.save() to prevent redundant
notifications by nova-cells in api cells from updates made in compute
cells.

Commit eaaa6593 used the Instance.skip_cells_sync() contextmanager
with Instance.save() in instance_update_at_top() to prevent update
cycles between api and compute cells, but the notification in
Instance.save() is not guarded by _sync_cells, so those notifications
generated in compute cells are also generated in api cells.

Change-Id: I16dca3c3691833931dba77cd700da64ee23f583c
Co-Authored-By: Philip Schwartz <philip.schwartz@rackspace.com>
Closes-Bug: #1516174

commit_message:
OpenStack typo

According to the word choice convention in
http://docs.openstack.org/contributor-guide/writing-style/word-choice.html
We should use OpenStack instead of Openstack.

Closes-bug: #1516634
Change-Id: I76a0273b2ef213e5dd865b5f31de01803aeca999

commit_message:
Get scoped token from ext_context middleware

Freshly introduced ext_context middleware produces unscouped token which
breaks authorization in Cloud Foundry service broker API.

Change-Id: Ibc85604dc9abed58c4c3bbeb92c572674fe74ff3
Closes-Bug: 1516635

commit_message:
Use os-collect-counters when appropriate

If a job is configured to use counters, and it passes, we want to
record these counters in the subunit stream as an attachment.

Change-Id: Iddb1fe50f2cf633e10e9fd1c92cef0de46ceba93
Implements: bp counter-inspection
Depends-On: Idbf74390a49cebae839f89d552aa6ced96feba79

commit_message:
Do not allow security group rule update

Neutron does not allow security group rules to be updated.  This
patch set removes the update support for security group rules.

Change-Id: I8748a7a274b3cbcbf4fc45598d8018ccaf95b082
Closes-Bug: #1464752

commit_message:
Add seek/tell methods to ChunkReader

...but only if the underlying reader exposes seek/tell. This should
allow swiftclient to retry uploads.

Closes-Bug: 1517447
Change-Id: I728028d9bd5967051ce43102c616aff116c15d6e

commit_message:
Cleanup - Remove js yaml, old index.html

Remove the javascript yaml library. We provide a json api. Lets
eat our own dog food. Also remove an unused copy of index.html.

Change-Id: Ica6a0eed8b867770a46564b471b0db5d35627222

commit_message:
Bump os-client-config requirement

The 1.11.0 release of os-client-config contains a bugfix for the
swift api timeout paramter issue. Be explicit that this version
of os-client-config is required for proper operation of shade.
The 1.11.1 release contains a bugfix for the 1.11.0 release.

Change-Id: Iabcb62593143473a7459ad01122a734d4230ab77

commit_message:
Refactor HP LeftHand driver to now be HPE

This patch refactors the HP LeftHand driver to be
HPE LeftHand.

This is being done because the company responsible for
this driver is now Hewlett Packard Enterprise (HPE).

The driver is now located in the cinder/volume/drivers/hpe
folder.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint rebrand-hp-lefthand-driver

commit_message:
Prepare neutron "use_namespaces" option removal

The neutron use_namespaces option is deprecated since Kilo, it's time
remove it from neutron, neutron-*aas and devstack. This change removes
use_namespaces option usage (without changing behavior) in
unit/functional tests in order to prepare option removal from neutron.

Partial-Bug: #1508188

Depends-On: I2fbf65df1250d9f9f1656b3964ee3b6de1ef1118
Change-Id: I84c1d3270448b1f085840d356532794974e5b31e

commit_message:
Functional: Add container creation/deletion on swarm bay.

This patch levearges docker api to create container and delete it on a TLS
enabled bay.

Also, added case of using non-tls client to access bay.

More actions will be added by following patches.

Partially implements: blueprint swarm-functional-testing
Change-Id: Ia3d2f0f3bf5f360940788998d52d734e544f8c0c

commit_message:
Add some comments about nova variable definition

Add comments in playbooks/roles/os_nova/defaults/main.yml,
mainly about nova_virt_type and nova_virt_autodetect.

Change-Id: I51ddfb44adc582c3c0ea47c7a4162881dfa2f7c3
(cherry picked from commit f35b6e2518ac7d2730e42f426918068da42a5be3)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-30 15:07:45.000000000', 'message': "Update neutron_migrations_facts

This change does the following to neutron_migrations_facts:

- uses --verbose option on neutron-db-manage current to determine state
  of migrations (this option is introduced in Mitaka and without it we
  had no way of determining which branch a revision was associated
  with)
- takes subproject migrations into account (neutron-lbaas as an
  example)
- adds run_contract / run_expand to MIGRATIONS so we can easily see if
  neutron or a subproject have pending migrations
- removes release and library_path options since these are no longer
  required
- removes get_branch method since we are able to obtain the information
  returned here from neutron-db-manage current --verbose

We also update neutron_db_setup.yml to use MIGRATIONS['run_contract']
and MIGRATIONS['run_expand'] to determine if neutron or a subproject
has migrations which need to be applied.

Closes-Bug: #1511756

Change-Id: I3a385f4530620718ba01a7b5e993ba08ce38f7c7

  had no way of determining which branch a revision was associated

  example)
- adds run_contract / run_expand to MIGRATIONS so we can easily see if
  neutron or a subproject have pending migrations
- removes release and library_path options since these are no longer
  required
- removes get_branch method since we are able to obtain the information
  returned here from neutron-db-manage current --verbose

We also update neutron_db_setup.yml to use MIGRATIONS['run_contract']
and MIGRATIONS['run_expand'] to determine if neutron or a subproject
has migrations which need to be applied.

Closes-Bug: #1511756

commit_message:
Update neutron_migrations_facts

This change does the following to neutron_migrations_facts:

- updates MIGRATIONS dict by adding entries for each neutron
  sub-project while also adding keys to track which sub-projects are
  installed and which migrations need to be run (contract or expand)
- takes subproject migrations into account (neutron-lbaas as an
  example)
- updates neutron_venv_lib_dir and neutron_non_venv_lib_dir by removing
  reference to neutron specifically since these vars need to be used
  for all neutron subprojects also

We also update neutron_db_setup.yml to use MIGRATIONS['run_contract']
and MIGRATIONS['run_expand'] to determine if neutron or a subproject
has migrations which need to be applied.

Closes-Bug: #1511756
Change-Id: I3a385f4530620718ba01a7b5e993ba08ce38f7c7

> Biggest sticking point is probably the pyeclib patching, but it seems worth it to let us move forward given that the patch is fairly specific and shouldn't break when upstream is fixed.

My sed command is a subset of the patch already sent to pyeclib. I sent my pull request 3 months ago, I ping them every 15 days (or even more frequently). I don't know how I can help them to get a review faster...

> Holding off on scoring for now, until I've had a chance to investigate dnspython3 and Swift's locale support.

My plan is to get as fast as possible a working tox -e py34 to make the python34 job voting, to avoid Python 3 regressions.

It's not possible to port Swift at once. I prefer to handle issues one by one.

I can help on porting dnspython to Python 3.

What are issues with locales?"}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-07-09 17:04:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Sorry, I meant sticking point for the Swift community at large. I totally get the reason behind the patching, and I think it's a reasonable tradeoff. We should remember to clean it up once upstream is fixed, but it shouldn't hurt anything if we don't get to it immediately. That said, I can only +1; we still need to get other people on board with it :P

I agree that the freeze-the-world approach isn't viable. It makes me sad that so much has to change just to be able to check *one* file which itself has only *one* swift import. I almost want to predicate PY3 compatibility on doing a massive code restructuring so we can approach this more sanely, but I think that would just further draw this out.

There already *is* a dnspython3 package [1]. It's put out by the same people, and the fact that they only have one set of docs seems to indicate it is (should be?) a drop-in replacement. We should use that rather than dropping the requirement.

The set of possible policy names is (apparently) locale-dependent. Replacing string.letters (which is locale-dependent) with string.ascii_letters (which isn't) introduces a potential landmine for operators when they go to upgrade from PY2 to PY3: policy names that used to be valid are now invalid. Is there any way to get a locale-aware set of letters in PY3 that would better map to string.letters from PY2?

Alternatively, the current restrictions are intentionally defensive and could be loosened [2]. I've started playing with a patch that would allow any UTF-8 string and get rid of VALID_CHARS entirely, but it'll still be at least a day or two before I've got that in a state suitable for review. And (as you've seen) it's hard to say how long it would take for it to actually land.

[1] https://pypi.python.org/pypi/dnspython3/

[2] https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/df134df/swift/common/storage_policy.py#L173"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-09 22:17:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

> There already *is* a dnspython3 package [1]. (...) We should use that rather than dropping the requirement.

Oh cool, I wasn't aware of it. We can try to use it.

My plan is to port more and more code, but do that incrementally. dnspython3 can be enabled later, when needed.

> The set of possible policy names is (apparently) locale-dependent. Replacing string.letters (which is locale-dependent) with string.ascii_letters (which isn't) introduces a potential landmine for operators when they go to upgrade from PY2 to PY3: policy names that used to be valid are now invalid.

Oh wow. It doesn't feel right to have a security based on the locale. The HTTP protocol doesn't use locales but the ISO-8859-1 encoding for HTTP headers. For me, it would be much safer to only accept ASCII letters. I'm talking about Python 2, not Python 3.

Note: If I recall correctly, Swift (OpenStack projects?) uses UTF-8 for HTTP headers, it doesn't respect the HTTP standard.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#HTTP

> Is there any way to get a locale-aware set of letters in PY3 that would better map to string.letters from PY2?

Python 3 doesn't use the C isalpha() function anymore, but a Py_ISALPHA() function which only uses ASCII (it is independant of the current locale).

The C isalpha() function is no more used nor exposed in Python.

> I've started playing with a patch that would allow any UTF-8 string (...)

Hum, that's a new feature, right?"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-09 22:30:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(6 comments)

Thanks Tim for your good review and all your suggestions. I will work on a new patch.

For me, the locale thing can be fixed later. It's not like Swift will be used on production on Python 3 tomorrow."}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-07-10 00:27:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

OK, I think I'm starting to see how this can move forward.

I'm comfortable with defering the locale issue, but only if we make it fail *very loudly* instead of rather subtly. As it's written now, it looks like string.ascii_letters is the PY3 equivalent of string.letters in PY2, which simply isn't true.

I'd still like to see dnspython3 getting included as a dependency, though. It shouldn't be too hard, though it may require a change to global-requirements."}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-10 08:36:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-10 08:36:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

with Python 3.

With this change and the change
Ie5d437cd396972d4143ffffb96ec3c289e221b08, the python34 check job
should pass. It becomes possible to make it voting to avoid Python 3
regressions.

This change adds a py34 test environment to tox.ini using a whitelist
of tests which pass on Python 3. Currently, only test_exceptions.py
of test/unit/common/ is run on Python 3

This change makes possible to port incrementally Swift to Python 3.
Tests will be ported one by one and added to the py34 test
environment when they pass. The final goal is to remove the whitelist
when all tests will pass on Python 3.

The py34 test environment patchs manually PyEClib 1.0.7 to port it to
Python 3. It's a temporary hack until Swift switchs to PyEClib 1.0.8
or newer (which supports Python 3). PyEClib 1.0.8 doesn't install
Jerasure (nor gf-complete) anymore, so the OpenStack infra should
install these libraries manually.

Change-Id: I5c8a9fe7b9635f1acab8f401908975fc6fc58c7a

commit_message:
py3: Add py34 test environment to tox

Add a py34 test environment to tox.ini using a whitelist
of tests which pass on Python 3. Currently, only test_exceptions.py
of test/unit/common/ is run on Python 3

Change-Id: I5c8a9fe7b9635f1acab8f401908975fc6fc58c7a

commit_message:
install ebtables locking workaround

ebtables is racing with itself when nova and libvirt attempt to create
rules at the same time in the nat table. ebtables now has an explicit
--concurrent flag, that all tools must opt into to prevent ebtables
from inherently being unsafe to run.

libvirt gained this support in 1.2.11, which is too new for our ubuntu
primary testing environment. Nova still hasn't added this support,
though even if it did, we'd run into the issue with libvirt.

We can do the most ghetto thing possible and create a wrapper for
ebtables that does explicit locking on it's own. It's pretty terrible,
but it should work. And it is the kind of work around that people
unable to upgrade libvirt will probably need to do.

This is an opt in value which we should set in the gate to True.

Related-Bug: #1501558

Change-Id: Ic6fa847eba34c21593b9df86a1c2c179534d0ba5
(cherry picked from commit 7860f2ba3189b0361693c8ee9c65d8d03fb115d6)
(cherry picked from commit aca08dedc789eb3286d435634674efb4e1885d5f)

commit_message:
Enabling strict di mode

Using strict DI mode will improve angular's performance when injecting
dependencies in injectable functions because it doesn't have to
dynamically discover a function's dependencies.

It is suggested by Angular official web site to use strict dependency
injection mode in production for get better performance:
https://docs.angularjs.org/guide/di#using-strict-dependency-injection

This patch fixes all the places where explicit di is not applied, and
then enables strict-di mode in production.

This is prioritized as CRITICAL for Horizon Mitaka release:
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/mitaka-horizon-priorities

Change-Id: I1c0e01d7ac9aec03d961f14ff7297bc98c513637
Implements: blueprint angular-performance-strict-di

Enable radix

This enables the radix linting rule from eslint-config-openstack,
and corrects any found errors.

Change-Id: Icfb8dd7a91770a84f94468693609093aedd31337

Enable no-unused-vars

Fix combination alarms

The combination are not evaluated correctly.
This change fixes that.

Closes-bug: #1511252

Reduced source code by extracting duplicated code

The clone metrics before and after the refactoring can be checked here:
 http://openqa.sed.hu/dashboard/index/2?did=4
The clone coverage is decreased by 20% (from 4.6% to 3.7%).

commit_message:
Put Session options into an option group

There are potentially a lot of options. Make sure Session options
are in a group like Auth options are.

Change-Id: I3e41f1ece0611a0cb7d9b8ab83cfa4bd0105b10d

commit_message:
Fix namespace regression for neutron

Due the to way network namespaces work, they will not survive a
container restart. This is not an issue related to Kolla or Neutron
but rather an issue with how network namespaces work.

This is putting back into place a workaround that was in correctly
removed in the past. We simply cleanup the namespace cruft when the
neutron-agents container restarts thus avoiding this issue.

Change-Id: Ic16f2f766b4fa46347ea14a1ece5a4653c69d779
Closes-Bug: #1511216

commit_message:
Clean up horizon httpd pid files for RPM distros

(apply same fix that we did for keystone, to horizon)

In some cases we're seeing httpd not cleaning up properly after itself,
which results in the horizon container failing to restart. This is
confirmed to happen on rpm based distros, but have not had any reports
on Ubuntu.

Change-Id: I8ece6da1a8a1180730d68be0d129a656ddcede07
Closes-Bug: #1515214
backport: liberty

commit_message:
Fix branch override in zuul-branch-git-prep

Rather than overriding ZUUL_BRANCH (which should not be overidden)
set the --branch argument to zuul cloner, which is the z-c equivalent
of OVERRIDE_BRANCH.

Change-Id: Ie40b668a3a33943a0431047d18716329c1e440c0

commit_message:
Stop using trunk python-troveclient in test runs

Because it has backward incompatible changes like:

I5ab58fd64f4745a2e558392bff649b05401ed57a

So the change here is to use the version of troveclient
from stable/kilo global-requirements.

We also sync up with global-requirements since (1) that's a thing
that needs to happen anyway and (2) we need to cap mock to get
the unit tests passing.

Also fixes the remaining unit tests that are failing.

Co-Authored-By: Craig Vyvial <cp16net@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Fix gate

A previous commit [1] removed the glance data container. Although this
worked at the time (as evident by it passing the gate) the drop root
patches merged after the gate patch causing the glance service to
not have the proper permissions to create this needed directory

[1] I7f2f5979b01807275908699d1243756cb97d3588

Change-Id: I5044de8d348e401a50970fd77671a79d35d2d595

commit_message:
Remove deprecated 'project usage list' command

Remove the 'project usage list' command that was deprecated in version
1.0.2 in review Ie08d4f88d71a660fca1862405351109cd0aa86b6.

Note that the removed command class is a good example of how to wrap a
command and show a deprecation message.

Change-Id: I6c750730963615895f5d9953487d2d5a905885a8

commit_message:
carbonara: implement an integer sampling attribute

Currently, the sampling attribute is a Pandas object that can be either
Nano or Seconds. This is not consistent, and exposes Pandas outside of
Carbonara, which is not a good idea.

This implements a public sampling attribute which always returns a float
of the number of seconds.

Change-Id: I2cf08ee7bb0727783131728eca08888ec047a4ef

subject: carbonara: make offset conversion consistent

commit_message:
Update Erasure Coding Overview doc to remove Beta version

The major functionality of EC has been released for Liberty and
the beta version of the code has changed to "transition to
production" period.  It is with caution that deployers use the
erasure coding storage policy for producation at large scale.

Change-Id: Id62a18359c819a8d9a85dfcf8f55a6127b5a1602

commit_message:
Change default host reserved memory to 2048MB from 512MB

Results from pmap of idle nova-compute:
  https://gist.github.com/jtaleric/addd9079d6cdf4f7cf42

Results from free -m and cat /proc/meminfo:
  https://gist.github.com/jtaleric/410130f09c2aad2dc7e9

bug: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1282644
Change-Id: I9b3ceecabfdae0a516cfc72886fde7b26cc68f82

commit_message:
Improve unit test: test_alarm_state_history

Make it easy to understand what data returned from InfluxDB and API.
See also https://review.openstack.org/#/c/246329/ .

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-07 22:12:48.000000000', 'message': 'Add atom priority ability

In situations where many atoms can execute at the same
time it is sometimes useful to denote that when this situation
happens that certain atoms should execute before other
atoms (or at least an attempt should be made to do this) instead
of being nearly arbitrary.

This adds a priority class attribute to the atom class (which
can be overriden or changed as needed) which is then used in
the runtime state machine to sort on so that tasks with higher
priority get submitted first.

Change-Id: I3dcc705959085cba167883c85278e394b5cb1d2b

commit_message:
Add atom priority ability

In situations where many atoms can execute at the same
time it is sometimes useful to denote that when this situation
happens that certain atoms should execute/revert before other
atoms (or at least an attempt should be made to do this) instead
of being nearly arbitrary.

This adds a priority class attribute to the atom class (which
can be overridden or changed as needed) which is then used in
the runtime state machine to sort on so that atoms with higher
priority get submitted (and therefore executed/reverted) first.

Closes-Bug: #1507755

Change-Id: I3dcc705959085cba167883c85278e394b5cb1d2b

are contradictory, and DEVSTACK_GATE_REGEX will take precedence.
So, this patch removes the TEMPEST_FULL variable. The second issue
is that regex used was wrong, and it was running more tests then was
intended, they also need to skip slow tests. Slow tests should not be
run as part of a gating job, because as the tag name implies, they are
too slow. (periodic and experimental are fine though) So this patch
corrects the regex to properly exclude slow and the test which exposes

commit_message:
Fix job definition for ceph-src jobs

The job definition for ceph-src was doing some weird stuff. First it
was setting both TEMPEST_FULL and a DEVSTACK_GATE_REGEX, those 2
are contradictory, and DEVSTACK_GATE_REGEX will take precedence.
So, this patch removes the TEMPEST_FULL variable. The second issue
is that regex used was wrong, and it was running more tests then was
intended, they also need to skip slow tests. Slow tests should not be
run as part of a gating job, because as the tag name implies, they are
too slow. (periodic and experimental are fine though) So this patch
corrects the regex to properly exclude slow and the test which exposes
where the ceph drivers break.

Change-Id: I4f70a3785ea4aeb38c3ebd8fd6a74ed3d035fa1a

commit_message:
Migrate monasca-ceilometer to be liberty compatible

List of changes:
* Changed oslo-incubator imports to oslo-service
* Refactored tests to functional and unit packages
* Upgraded test requirement versions
* Added py34 test capability
* Upgraded hacking(pep8) version
* Added devstack plugin and settings to deploy Ceilosca
* Modified setup.cfg to use liberty entry points
* Refactored storage driver to compatible with v2 api liberty changes

Change-Id: Id6711e6661cde14df3decba6f56e52d391981f42

commit_message:
Refactor authorize() method in wsgi.py

Almost every API method written in Manila performs
a policy check against relevant policies in etc/policy.json.
A method - authorize() was introduced in
manila/api/openstack/wsgi.py
in commit e4428f5e6c324a674c76f81340e1c94a956b4c6c
to perform these policy checks.

This patch refactors the authorize() method as a decorator
for consistency and easy usage in APIs that choose to
implement the policy check prior to any core logic.

Prior unit tests are modified for the APIs impacted through
this change.

The Cgsnapshots controller's policies are corrected for
name consistency without impacting behavior.

Change-Id: Ib34e166ab65513f8f02215c6569175fc9a913244
Closes-Bug: #1515397

commit_message:
Remove juno backwards compat jobs from tempest

The final juno release was just pushed. There is no longer upstream
support for the juno branch, so let's remove the jobs from tempest
since they are no longer needed.

Change-Id: I094d0f95fe74d551c2dce307510a3bf659010c2b

commit_message:
Add a bandit target to tox.ini

This requires some changes in the Python code, because bandit considers:

    try:
        <some code>
    except <some error>:
        pass

as an issue, since it might be an involuntarily unhandled error.

So this pattern is changed to something else when easily doable. Otherwise,
"nosec" is added when the code is obviously safe.

Change-Id: Ic99f29b944892fb78814f5de515e6ed699979bc1

commit_message:
Python Server

This enables the server to be switched over to being Python
rather than just doing static files. This allows for:
 * Dynamic API.
 * Faster loads due to supporting compression of Javascript.
 * Javascript/CSS from local webserver rather then remote.
 * XStatic managed Javascript/CSS.
 * Sharing code between the app-catalog and Horizon.

This patch set enables most of the infrastructure to do that
and copies in the initial website. Minimal changes have been
made to the site to make it compatible with the new code.

Further reviews will switch the site to use more of the new
functionality.

Co-Authored-By: Christopher Aedo <doc@aedo.net>

Change-Id: I2fa9686d3e5db4ee43a02aa7d09b998472e02bf6

commit_message:
Fix client backwards compatibility

Change [1] introduced support of microversions to manilaclient and
changed behaviour of client init that is not compatible with old
approach. Also, not all old modules have deprecated modules in place.

So, first problem description:
- Old client expected string with api version, new one expects
APIVersion class instance. So, add support for both and cover them with
unit tests.

Second problem description:
- Manila UI project imports "manilaclient.v1.contrib.list_extensions"
directly, but this file was moved to another place without keeping in
place deprecated variant. So, add such to fix backward compatibility
and allow to use newest manilaclient with manila-ui project.

[1] I3733fe85424e39566addc070d42609e508259f19

Change-Id: I838631fb38b8ddf1f4f1e06269af122bf51a5155
Closes-Bug: #1518245

commit_message:
Make cinder/udev post tasks dependent on is_metal flag.

The cinder/udev tasks can't be executed when the cinder
service is running on bare metal servers.
This fix excludes certain udev changes targeted for cinder volumes
container when running bare metal.

Change-Id: I2dbd8c2f290acd1016ca0aaf75ddf9d193768deb
Closes-Bug: #1514918

commit_message:
Allow 'forever_retry_uncaught_exceptions' to take in different defaults

Hard coding the delays in this function never quite seemed
to make sense (and no docs/comments were added as to why they
were fixed to the values they were set at) so allow those values
to change so that the API is cleaner and more flexible (and can
target a larger set of use-cases).

Change-Id: Id29767634bc46bec7b6e979a4531d24f9fab61e9

commit_message:
Allow health check results to provide there own details

When in detailed mode, show the provided details in a nicely
formatted table (or json) so that the user of the healthcheck
middleware can gain more insight into the result that was
produced.

Change-Id: I2fc1f7588ee628990d78b15ad337bd0eebbe8fb3

commit_message:
Add basic doc on using shotgun

Using shotgun itself solves several problems that can not
be solved by using fuel api

Change-Id: Idd9a0292b46a1890eeba03692c8d8b401d3ab947
Closes-Bug: 1420054

commit_message:
Use current valueName for zuul-stats singlestats

Right now, the values we display are averages, which is confusing
to people.  Setting valueName to current, we'll actually display the
current count for singlestats.

Change-Id: Icb1a62fb8b289165679ceec16e7d65dab98bf602
Depends-On: I4df8d130fce45cf58b01808997fc561cf8c4b42d
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

We really need this script but as well we need better implementation.
The code at the same time is "overdesigned" and "hardcoded" and it's hardcoded in places that should be flexible and overdesigned in places that should be hardcoded. 

And here is the way how to do it. 

All clients have the quite close to each other strucutre. To list the things you should use one of next methods: 

client.<resource>.list or client.list_<resource>s

Another thing that we should take in account are arguments of this method. so you need to specify for each resource corresponding arguments, and the thrid things is checker whatever is possible to call this method or not. 

So basically you need to implement few helper methods helpers

   def list1(client, project, resource_name, *args, **kwargs): 
       return getattr(getattr(client, project), resource_name).list(*args, **kwargs)

   def list2(client, project, resource_name, *args, **kwargs):
     return getattr(getattr(client, project), "list_%ss" ^ resource_name)(*args, **kwargs)
  
   def supported_always(clients, resource): 
       return True

    #you need as well one constant list: 

    RESOURCES = [
       ["nova", "servers", always_supported, list1, (,), {}], 
       ["nova", "flavors", always_supported, list2, (,), {}], 
       ....
    ]

   and you need one small method that will iterate over this resources: 

    dat_method(clients, resources): 
      result = {}
      for r in resources: 
          result["%s.%s" % r[0:2] ] = [] if not r[2](clients) else r3(clients, r[0], r[1] r[4], r[5])

      return result 
       
         
This code will much shorter, simpler to extend and much safer to use.'}, {'account_id': 10475, 'date': '2015-11-12 17:42:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 14817, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:40:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
[Ci] Get changes in resources after task run

This patch adds module tests.ci.osresources, which saves listing
of most important cloud resources before task run, and makes
comparison with another listing after task is complete.

Now we can check if there is a resources leak in cleanup

Change-Id: I5338c77ebd9390ec74a3f1a2028cc0b1ea1b51cf

host3/fc_host/host3

As with FC devices we want the domain:bus:device.function of the device.
For FCoE devices this is listed prior to `net`.

commit_message:
Parse FCoE sysfs device paths

FCoE devices have slightly different sysfs device paths to FC devices :

/sys/devices/pci0000:20/0000:20:03.0/0000:21:00.2/net/ens2f2/ctlr_2/
host3/fc_host/host3

As with FC devices we want the domain:bus:device.function of the device.
For FCoE devices this is listed prior to `net`.

Change-Id: I2e46af1679982964c0d90289bcf1a1fc702fcb15

commit_message:
_carbonara: dedicated methods to store raw timeserie

This patches introduces _{get,store}_unaggregated_timeserie methods for
Carbonara-based drivers. It allows to really handle aggregated
timeseries and the unaggregated timeserie with different code path.

It's cleaner (and it'll come handy later when splitting TimeSerieArchive).

Change-Id: If779c19f14c7295b17a796fb29c30932f1590eb5

commit_message:
cli: allow to upgrade in 2 passes

This adds 2 new option to `gnocchi-upgrade`:
- `--index-only' which only upgrades the index
- `--storage-only' which only upgrade the storage

Change-Id: I0c0b453495ac3df9600bc53abb7837764303b8b5

commit_message:
Avoid from storing samples with empty or not numerical volumes

In some cases Ceilometer receives notifications with 'counter_volume' equal
None, for ex. from glance when empty image was created. This patch adds check
to avoid storing samples with None or not numerical volumes.

Closes-Bug: #1484117
Closes-Bug: #1508220
Change-Id: Ic4b87c05d16dba765f601ca346b198eda7c91bea
(cherry-picked from commit 804de4ef2f26e1892dc2580fe16897b14741a13a)

commit_message:
Use ServiceList object rather than direct db call

The scheduler driver should use the ServiceList object rather than a
direct db call to get all services by topic.

Change-Id: I7fb8a52e8283aa6d47b91b49bbcf76495b289946
Closes-Bug: #1514863

commit_message:
config options: centralize section "serial_console"

The config options of the "nova.conf" section "serial_console"
got moved to the new central location "nova/conf/serial_console.py".

The way the centralization is done establishes a directed non-cyclic
dependency:

    functional-module (e.g. virt.libvirt.driver.py)
        => nova.conf.__init__.py
            => section_module (e.g. nova.conf.serial_console.py)

Which makes me believe that the "import_opt" calls are not necessary to
ensure that the proper module gets imported under the cover. That's why
I removed these "import_opt" calls. bp centralize-config-options

A subsequent patch will then improve the help texts.

bp centralize-config-options

Change-Id: I597f427455e976892f60262cc823be3946c83e88

commit_message:
Delete python bytecode before every test run

Because python creates pyc files during tox runs, certain
changes in the tree, like deletes of files, or switching
branches, can create spurious errors.

Change-Id: Id8798992dd71d9a7b16cba9e822bab236f0fcad7
Closes-Bug: #1368661

commit_message:
Set DIB_INSTALLTYPE_puppet_modules for master/stable

Currently we override in CI so we install puppet modules from source
for master, meaning that using tripleo.sh without manually overriding
the DIB_INSTALLTYPE doesn't work (the pinned modules are too old).

Conversely, for stable/liberty, we want to use the stable packaged
version as building from-master modules won't work.

Change-Id: I07f3bf081feb4a2dad649600cd67a5c80f6a04a9

commit_message:
Fix lack of parenthesis around boolean logic

The legacy envvar prefix support broke a workaround for use of OS_
envvars in test cases. This is only currently a problem for shade functional
tests, but it IS a bug.

Change-Id: Ia0cbb4e2ea7ce6eeeea36533e057bd53a830d44c

+1 for the code, but I'm concerned about entity name DashboardEntry. It means "an entry on the cluster's Dashboard tab". It was valid for the time when we were going to have link to plugin dashboard only on the cluster's Dashboard tab. 

Now we're also going to have link to dashboards for the plugin itself - the same entity with the same format, but for plugin, not for cluster. And it will not be shown on the dashboard (because dashboard is the tab of the cluster's page). So I guess we should rename it and also URL and update the spec accordingly.

I think the new names should be ClusterPluginDashboardLink and PluginDashboardLink, but your suggestions are welcome.

I'm ok with doing it in a separate patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8776, 'date': '2015-11-20 16:18:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

commit_message:
API for dashboard entries

 - Dashboard entry DB model and DB migration logic added,
 - Handler, json schema and validation added,
 - Serializer added,
 - Dashboard entires info added into statistics,
 - Public url for Dashboard entry creation.

Implements blueprint post-deployment-dashboard

commit_message:
Use "GiB" and "gibibyte" labels in share panels

Data storage sizes are typically measured in gibibytes (GiB).
To avoid confusion, Manila-ui panels should use these terms
instead of gigabytes and GB.

Change-Id: I98a0be1397fbf937c26fa033b96c2e8bcf5d4e27
Closes-bug: #1516839

commit_message:
Remove unused Manila API methods

There is two reasons to remove 'list_extensions' function:
- Manila UI does not use API method "list_extensions".
- Manila API v2 has made all extensions as core API and this
function becomes useless.

Change-Id: Ied4d49e92f3ebfb237787b9b6196ff9886e8de9a

Looks good to me. Thanks for cleaning up this bug.'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-11-16 12:17:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Making such changes without any comment in the config could raise issues in the future when multithreaded test run will be needed.

Concurrency should be configured in a right way. Current fix looks like a hack'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2015-11-16 12:36:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ivan,

First of all, configuration via lib config can not be hack. It is configuration.

Second, the fact that "setUpClass" runs more than one time is a bug, very expensive bug.

Best fix would be fix of testrepository runner. Exactly it should handle class and test runs properly.

Until it happens, updated cinderclient's config for testrepository to exclude appearance of the bug.

And third, current change does not block usage of multithreading. All separate test classes still are able to run in parallel.

So, do I understand you correctly that "adding comment to config" would be enough in current situation?'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-11-16 14:05:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-11-16 14:05:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Looks like I've misunderstood what this patch does"}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2015-11-16 21:16:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

for what it's worth, running the functional tests takes about 10 seconds longer to run with this patch than without.
So, what is the the original problem that this patch is trying to solve.   Don't want want to run tests in multiple threads to speed up execution ?

The original bug looks like it's filed against the manila client.

Ran 19 tests in 66.952s (-9.090s)

vs

Ran 19 tests in 76.042s (-0.218s)"}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2015-11-19 10:22:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Walter,

Сommit message and my comment-answer for Ivan answer your questions. Please, reread them. Nothing to do with your -1.

For the moment, this commit prevents future resources leak when Cinderclient functional tests start use class methods for resource setup that is just not used right now.

Soon or later, it should be fixed.'}, {'account_id': 1736, 'date': '2015-11-19 11:19:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Valeriy, if this patch is not needed right now, why do we need it?'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2015-11-19 12:00:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ivan,

I propose bugfix, if you think cinderclient does not need it because it does not suffer from it yet, then, please, set "won't fix" status to bug-report and I will abandon this change.'}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2015-11-19 18:55:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

As a side note, I don't see where setUpClass is ever declared/used inside of the cinderclient/tests dir."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-11-19 19:11:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2015-11-20 17:41:57.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-26 13:25:01.000000000', 'message': "Fix usage of setUpClass method in functional tests

Class method 'setUpClass' is executed for each test of test suite that
appeared in new thread. It leads to creation of redundant resources,
and, hence, waste of resources.

So, add 'group_regex' option in testr config that will make all tests
of each class run in one thread.

Change-Id: I0a7dc48ba19ed8b6b7f178444571b7da758e530d
Closes-Bug: #1509460
"}]
commit_message:
Fix usage of setUpClass method in functional tests

Class method 'setUpClass' is executed for each test of test suite that
appeared in new thread. It leads to creation of redundant resources,
and, hence, waste of resources.

So, add 'group_regex' option in testr config that will make all tests
of each class run in one thread.

Change-Id: I0a7dc48ba19ed8b6b7f178444571b7da758e530d
Closes-Bug: #1509460

commit_message:
Delete ports when nova fails to boot VM

This patch adds some code to the exception handler in the instance
manager's boot method to cleanup any created ports if nova fails to boot
the instance.

Change-Id: I459ccd82a367fcd41d4a894b7231c797dc5100e9
Closes-Bug: #1516152

commit_message:
Provide alias to oslo_messaging.notify._impl_messaging

Ifb96c2ae9868426cac2700bf4917c27c02c90b15 moved the _impl_messaging
module to oslo_messaging.notify.messaging which breaks neutron.

Neutron is fixed on master for mitaka but neutron on stable/liberty
is broken, and changing neutron on stable/liberty to use the new
path would require a global-requirements minimum version bump for
oslo.messaging to 2.6.0, which we want to avoid for people that have
already shipped liberty.

So provide an alias to the moved module so neutron in stable/liberty
continues to work. We deprecate the module so consumers know they
need to upgrade and move off this. We may need to cap oslo.messaging
in global-requirements on stable/liberty at some point when we remove
the deprecated alias module.

Change-Id: I29453e0fbf30b0a571c2b1afc7cc81d1a11535f0
Closes-Bug: #1513630

Nova-libvirt needs to bind to /sys/fs/cgroup

Nova-compute was mounting in /sys/fs/cgroup when the libvirt
container is the one that actually needs it.

commit_message:
Add local docker registry support

Create a set of environment variables that allows us to configure
a docker registry for deployment.  This patch assumes there is a
local docker registry already setup with the images loaded in place.

Change-Id: Iaafaf23eb3fa8b24bcd8f73bb38c552bea629607
Signed-off-by: Ian Main <imain@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Hallisey <rhallise@redhat.com>

subject: Update docker compute environment to use json config

commit_message:
Update docker compute environment to use json config

In liberty, Kolla copies around files and runs the service given
a specified command, by reading a json file.

This will update the existing work to follow that template by
creating a json file for each of the services and pushing it
into the containers.

Change-Id: I5085d1896ea965fd8854765b055068a5ad30bcfd
Co-Authored-By: Jeff Peeler <jpeeler@redhat.com>

Currently some tests leave databases after execution.
These databases consume significant amount of disk space.
And sometimes their existence cause errors (see bug description)

This patch partially solves the problem as it only affects functional
tests.
It will implement "tearDownClass(cls)" method in "FunctionalTestBase"
class which will drop databases used by functional tests and close
connections at the end of execution of each test subclass.

But there's performance problem.
The implementation of "tearDownClass(cls)" reopens connections to drop
databases. Opening/closing connections consumes significant time.
Same for dropping databases.
Overall this patch makes functional test execution time 35% slower.
On my machine it's: 20 seconds vs 27 seconds.

I was searching for a solution to compensate this slowdown.
Now I know supereffective way to reduce functional tests execution time
to just 5 seconds. I can describe this possible solution in my next bug
report, for example.

commit_message:
Automatically drop functional tests databases

Currently some tests leave databases after execution.
These databases consume significant amount of disk space.
And sometimes their existence causes errors (see bug description)

This patch partially solves the problem as it only affects functional
tests.
It will implement "tearDownClass(cls)" method in "FunctionalTestBase"
class which will drop databases used by functional tests and close
connections at the end of execution of each test subclass.

Class method "_pooling_drop_dbs_by_project(cls, xproject)" uses not very
straightforward way to drop databases of each pool driver, but it makes
these databases to drop even in integration mode. Please tell me if you
know a better way to do it.
Cleanups in "TestHealth" class were removed as they prevent dropping of
pool databases.

But there's performance problem.
The implementation of "tearDownClass(cls)" reopens connections to drop
databases. Opening/closing connections consumes significant time.
Same for dropping databases.
Overall this patch makes functional test execution time +50% longer.
On my machine it's: 20 seconds vs 27 seconds.

I was searching for a solution to compensate this slowdown.
Now I know super effective way to reduce functional tests execution time
to just 5 seconds. The description of this possible solution can be
found in my new bug report:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/zaqar/+bug/1516343

Partial-Bug: 1506091
Change-Id: Ib4addfee5feadf8c75218da0cbeea56b0830f0a8

commit_message:
Fix issue with system installed xtrabackup

The change adds a task to ensure that the system provided
xtrabackup package is removed before installing the downloaded
version using the deb. This is required to ensure that there
are no version conflicts when installing the package.

The change also corrects the version of the galera server repo
in the defaults directory. While the repo correct version of
mariadb is being installed the name of the assumed repo is wrong.

Closes-Bug: #1513459

Change-Id: I63cb546cf5a4386320f01ed6f2120dd7c8341335
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit 19a174be954046003ff572b8f34b0945228bc3b1)

Juan, Dave, I can fix up this file to be easier to use and write some Tests for coverage in a future patch.

I want it to be easier to use:

Instead of having to do:

pkcs11-key-generation --library-path {library_path here}
--passphrase {HSM password here} --slot-id {HSM slot here} mkek --length 32
--label 'HMACLabelHere'
MKEK successfully generated!

I think it would be better as:

pkcs11-key-generation mkek --library-path {library_path here}
--passphrase {HSM password here} --slot-id {HSM slot here}  --length 32
--label 'HMACLabelHere'
MKEK successfully generated!

and if --library-path {library_path here}
--passphrase {HSM password here} --slot-id {HSM slot here} are not input we can prompt for them, throw excepts if incorrect, etc.

Let me know your opinion. Thanks :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-20 17:10:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+2

commit_message:
Allow length to be passed in MKEK Creation

Allows length argument to be passed in MKEK Creation. There is
a bug where it fails, therefore the user can only have the
default 32 value.

Change-Id: I0cfd8d5690fd781419ece79bbb0337a2fe8fef49
Closes-Bug: #1480735

commit_message:
Refactor the datastore manager classes (more)

This moves most of the rest of the boiler-plate code
into the base class.

This includes more filesystem methods, the 'unsupported'
methods and a configuration method.
It also consolidates the replication strategy.

The prepare_completed flag was also prefixed with a
double underscore to make it difficult for descendant
classes to change it by accident.

Log messages were also enhanced.

Partially Implements: blueprint datastore-manager-refactor
Change-Id: I2010ffd8e8f480b12b0cfd30ffc948a7c8963bd8

commit_message:
Skip test that rely on creds by role

The legacy credential providers raises an exception when
is_role_available is invoked. This causes tests that rely on
credentials by role to fail rather than skip when that
credential provider is used.

The wrong behaviour was introduced in change
I351f86f0570070105bbf24f2d904e917feea6e57, and since than it's
causing periodic and experimental jobs using the legacy
credential provider to fail. Fixing that.

Change-Id: I0ca0b96fc618ffe60851984a9c6d46b0507878d4

Move restarting inspector before building images to give it time to come up

Previously we had random failures due to inspector start up taking longer
then hardcoded 5 seconds.

[{'created': '2015-11-19 09:52:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fedora 23 supported

This change allows to use f23 without the FORCE=yes option.

Make sure you have latest kernel, or you have kernel-modules
installed for the running kernel.

f21 support will be removed when the gate jobs are upgraded

commit_message:
Fedora 23 supported

This change allows to use f23 without the FORCE=yes option.

Make sure you have latest kernel, or you have kernel-modules
installed for the running kernel.

f21 support will be removed when the gate jobs are upgraded
to use newer fedora version.

Change-Id: I6e3e64088187a7f6da745e3cfb07524fd31782ab

commit_message:
Add OpenStack project networking-wan.

The Neutron extension networking-wan is intended to support various
WAN connectivity patterns. These patterns include but are not limited
to private backbone, hybrid-cloud, router peering, tiered WAN
services and WAN SLAs.

The project is described here (additional updates, architectures
and workflows forthcoming):

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/WAN

Change-Id: Ib1c574bd0d72dd5b7357be3a0322c2cbcff94be6

'}, {'created': '2015-07-22 06:56:54.000000000', 'message': 'Add Stackforge project Fusion.

Fusion is a higher order logic engine that implements new workflows to
support various types of multi-datacenter WAN federation use cases and interconnections
leveraging OpenStack APIs and services.

The project is described here (further updates, use cases and architecture
forthcoming):

commit_message:
Add OpenStack project Fusion.

Fusion is a controller for multi-cloud WAN capacity management,
governance and brokering. It leverages the APIs of multiple
OpenStack deployments and third party entities to facilitate various
tiers of service and degrees of compliance with regional laws to
facilitate multi-cloud WAN interconnections.

The project is described here (further updates, use cases and
architecture forthcoming):

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Fusion

Change-Id: Ic158f75f268e818883a2905c058953a632d447ad

commit_message:
Fuel-devops dos.py show env occurs exception

The Environment.DoesNotExist exception will be generated
because django will not found corresponding model.
shell.py will be invoked by dos.py and
shell.py module gets 'env' by name which was passed through CI
where 'env' object shall be taken from settings
stored in database before.
If requested 'env' is not presented in database then
django lib throw exception but shell.py module
don't intercept it and it is root cause.

The Environment.DoesNotExist shall be intercepted
in shell.py in init function and reasonable message
shall be shown in this case.
We will be blocked to continue work with odd 'env'
which is not presented in database because 'env' is
shell.py public methods.
in this case we have to return error to CI and let to know
another processes that we was failed.

Closes-Bug: #1515258

Change-Id: I15c3e47867c5d4c168ae510110c46acde8933841

commit_message:
libvirt: make detach_device to return an async object

libivrt.detachDeviceFlags is an async operation and we should to wait
for the process to have been executed and well finiched.  This commit
adds return to the method detach_device to make possible such process.

Closes-Bug: bug/1436561
Change-Id: Ia2eeff8b30901a2dcbd730b5ac672f123db161aa

commit_message:
Update jobs for mistral

Updated mistral gates configuration, substitute job definition to
job template, split one mistral-devstack gate into two which will
run different suite of tests.

commit_message:
Datapath on L2pop only for agents with tunneling-ip

This patch is a regression issue for patch[1].

Only those agents which expose tunneling-ip will be considered in
determining data-path tunnels in deployments with l2pop ON.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236970/

Change-Id: I7c3b911d5e7448b4e8dee15bb50df33a6e9d5cfe
Closes-Bug: #1407959
(cherry picked from commit 311c9d9d929b4a53d2f54824e599c12f653b77f6)

commit_message:
Switch to using neutron.common.utils:replace_file()

neutron.agent.linux.utils:replace_file() and
neutron.common.utils:replace_file() have same functionality.

This is the 3rd patch in the series of 4 patches.

Partial-bug: #1504477
Depends-On: Id1a7f1236786e8606c91bb9925cd9ac8e95892b3

commit_message:
Switch to eslint.

This ports over changes made in openstack-health to convert the
project from jshint to eslint, with the eslint-config-openstack
plugin.

Change-Id: Iaa0490d07603e2481e1c738136f9fda1be95dea8

A superclass exception (error) is being handled before

Trivial Fix

commit_message:
Bad exception clauses order

A superclass exception (error) is being handled before
a sub class exception(SSLError) which is making the latter
exception clause unreachable. Corrected the order of these
exception clauses.

Trivial Fix
Change-Id: I82e6f4984b095f50cdd7ffccd9af60ce75d41f7f

Removed unused settings.py.

A residual settings.py configuration file was forgotten while
removing Django. This removes it.

commit_message:
Add note about upgrading primary controller first

Primary controller usually has the lowest ID number of all controllers
in the environment. Add note to select controller with minimal ID to
upgrade first in Upgrade Environment section of the Operations Guide.

Closes-bug: 1505641
Change-Id: I35b8440b6a4655c197b2b694e26f6760e6adad11

commit_message:
Replace neutron-specific LengthStrOpt with StrOpt

max_length option was added to StrOpt in oslo.config 2.7.0.
Neutron-specific LengthStrOpt is no longer required.

Change-Id: Icfecb5c8c68c942fca847e27a0c1862f18bdcdca
Closes-Bug: #1518178

commit_message:
Move data container to start.yml

The original reason for having the data container in the bootstrap.yml
was to keep consistency with rabbitmq and mariadb, but in light of
this bug we need to move the data container out of the bootstrap.yml
role since we will be limiting the hosts that those tasks can run on.

Change-Id: I7f2f5979b01807275908699d1243756cb97d3588
Partial-Bug: #1513598

The response may not have a body in certain error conditions, like
a 500 on a socket error as seen in the VMware NSX CI. This fixes
an AttributeError when trying to access the response body in those
cases.

Change-Id: I086bb5bdb59813d326d45b5f7545da2ebb12aa95
Closes-Bug: #1517275
(cherry picked from commit b709dd62c16ffb0d924bf25328e29a3fbec0f36a)
'}]
commit_message:
vmware: check for response body in error conditions

The response may not have a body in certain error conditions, like
a 500 on a socket error as seen in the VMware NSX CI. This fixes
an AttributeError when trying to access the response body in those
cases.

Change-Id: I086bb5bdb59813d326d45b5f7545da2ebb12aa95
Closes-Bug: #1517275
(cherry picked from commit b709dd62c16ffb0d924bf25328e29a3fbec0f36a)

commit_message:
Support for multiple UCS Managers

Cisco ML2 UCS Manager plugin us being extended to support multiple UCS
Manager instances within a single Openstack cloud.

Conflicts:
	All other files to be backported are in the networking-cisco project.

Depends-On: I890470a17b522b6e39a2578937c0537bcf4c09cf
Change-Id: I890470a17b522b6e39a2578937c0537bcf4c09cf
Partial-Bug: #1491025

commit_message:
Add checks for VIPs network mapping

VIPs from network roles with mapping to non-existing network should be skipped
from assignment.
Added NeutronManager80 and AllocateVIPs80Mixin

Change-Id: Id8dd1d26872edd1e8055de5ebcaa2d7dd9a955f7
Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)

(12 comments)

Overall, this looks great. Two comments here and then a bunch in-line with the code.

1. Minor change, could do it now or in a subsequent change: I'd like to see  the `resp=resp.json()` and `return resp` lines folded together while we're moving away from the calling `.body` in-line with the old session verb calls.

2. I noticed a pattern I'd like to try and clean up in another change around how we used to have accept=None in the session.verb methods, but now we're constructing a bunch of {"Accept": ''} dicts in a lot of places to replace that. There's a whole bunch of places where we do exactly that, and there's a bunch where we're setting an "Accept" key on an existing header dict. That might actually be something to work with in KSA itself, or something we slap on top, but either way it's something to consider.

I'd like to see #1 done while we're here, but if you don't want to do it here I'll take care of it once this is merged.'}, {'account_id': 8736, 'date': '2015-11-11 19:10:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 31.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-11 20:03:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Verified+1

commit_message:
Prevent to use physnet definition while creating 'local' networks

This is a intermediate solution on the way to dynamic physnets
and networks creation.

Change-Id: I53cf1c67b82ef8b14f2e1d69f22985ca6a69c0e6
Closes-bug: #1517853
blueprint: dyn-gen-physnet-set

commit_message:
devstackgaterc: Tweak plugin path for Kilo

Tweak devstack configuration for Kilo, where the new plugin path
is not available.

This change goes into stable/kilo directly as it isn't
appropriate for liberty and later.

Closes-Bug: #1516896
Change-Id: Iccd06ebefa76c1f240a04d10eeb0e40d1c15c7e0

commit_message:
devstackgaterc: Tweak L3 plugin configuration for Kilo

Tweak devstack configuration for Kilo, where we don't have
a separate L3 plugin.

This change goes into stable/kilo directly as it isn't
appropriate for liberty and later.

Closes-Bug: #1516899
Change-Id: I96da3d3b5b77f48170c5e2f6278767723b0a9836

commit_message:
Use server_profile_template_uri at scheduling

Since Server Profile Templates define configuration options that can change
important characteristics of a node, it is important to make this property
available in Nova flavors. That way the scheduler selects a node with accurate
configuration.

This patch moves the server_profile_template_uri from driver_info to
properties/capabilities so the user can use a properly defined flavor to
get a node with an appropriate configuration.

Co-Authored-By: Gabriel Assis Bezerra <gabrielb@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I543a07c8978fae4adc29ccd23e7943429aa3186a

commit_message:
Revert "devstack: Use midonet stable/v2015.06.2 by default"

This reverts commit dfe8a37dff90f000e24368be271211e5505ccd7e.

Because:
- it's wrong for v2 job
- it's no longer necessary as v1 job now
  specifies MIDONET_BRANCH explicitly [1]

[1] 9fddd82c7c9784ff86d459c584df48834193c0a5

Change-Id: I3855388587723e8d842556d5b62235aa492c097d
Closes-Bug: #1516898
Related-Bug: #1482080
